In the present work, the free energy profile for the Na+ along the migration channel is calculated by mapping F(r%s) as a function of the distance of the location, r%s, with respect to any two of its nearest Na1-sites, l, under periodic boundary conditions. Note that the mapping of F(r%s) from space coordinates, r%s, to F(l), is in the spirit of introducing a ‘reaction coordinate’, which reduces the dimensionality of the information and helps to visualize the free energy profile along the migration channel.
Below, we shall note certain technicalities of the mapping procedure:
The separation between two neighboring Na1 sites (B6.4 Å) is divided into fine bins (of size 0.1 Å). The distance r%s1(i) = r%s À r%1(i), where r%1(i) is the location of the ith Na1 site, is searched over all Na1 sites in the simulation cell. Whenever this distance is less than 6.4 Å under PBCs, F(r%s) is cumulated in an appropriate bin, say indexed j, which spans the reaction coordinate, l. The quantity is then averaged over the counts registered in each bin. That is,

F(lj) = hF(PBC(r%s1(i)))ij, if r%s1(i) o 6.4 Å

(5)

