where h. . .ij represent the average over the trajectory in a given bin j. It should be noted that with the migration channel being the one connecting two neighboring Na1 (which shall be demonstrated in the later sections), for every hill-drop location, r%s, there would be two i values (that is, Na1 sites), which would meet the above criterion. It should be remarked further that the above mapping procedure is not unique and any other method of mining F(r%s) data onto repeating segments of trajectories may also be employed.
The free-energy profile from MTD simulation is compared with other compatible quantities, such as the potential energy profile of individual Na+ ions, and potential energy barrier employing nudged-elastic-band (NEB) calculations, detailed as below:
(1) The potential energy profile: the average potential energy of individual Na+ ions at a given location, r%i, due to all the rest of the ions in the system,

