The Na+–Na+ RDF (Fig. 4), calculated from the MTD trajec-

tory, offers insights on the ion transport in the system. The first

peak of the RDF appears at around 6.3 Å, which measures the

distance between two neighbouring Na1 sites (6b positions of the R3%c space group). The second peak at around 9.1 Å

corresponds to the next-neighbour distance between two Na1 sites. This reflects the fact that in NaZr2(PO4)3, all the Na+ ions prefer to occupy the Na1 sites, and also Na+ hops occur from

one Na1 to the nearest Na1 site. Most experimental and

computer simulation studies on this material have suggested this mechanism earlier.49–51,58,59

For better convergence of the free energy profile, the ‘tagged’

particle needs to sample a significant fraction of the individual

local minima and the saddle points connecting them. For

instance, in Fig. 5, the free energy barrier measures 0.24 eV

after 10 ns, while from 20 ns onward, the barrier starts conver-

ging, and settles to the value of 0.34 eV over the period of

100 ns.

Fig. 6 shows the free energy (eqn (4) and (5)) and potential

energy profiles (eqn (6)) calculated from the entire MTD trajec-

tory of 100 ns, along with that from the NEB calculations. The

barriers calculated from diﬀerent profiles show comparable values ranging between B0.35 and 0.4 eV. It should be noted

that all the energy profiles indicate an energy minimum at the

Na1 sites, and the saddle point is located at the Na2 site. This is in agreement with the Na+–Na+ dynamic RDF shown in Fig. 4, wherein the Na+ ions preferentially occupy the Na1 sites in

NaZr2(PO4)3. The calculated values of the microscopic barriers are also in good agreement with the previous studies.60,61

