during the period. Thus, the Na+ transport remains inaccessible due to the long time scales of the process. Fig. 8 (bottom) shows the MTD trajectory of the single Na+ ion on which the external potential is applied. Due to its slower transport, the Na+ ion could not explore the simulation box suﬃciently during the 100 ns of time (shown in red) initially dedicated. Hence, the simulation was continued for another 100 ns of MTDsimulation (shown in olive green). The mean squared displacement of Na+ ions calculated from the MTD trajectory (averaged over all Na+ ions and over several time-origins, as in the previous case) is presented in Fig. 9.
Fig. 10 shows the Na+–Na+ RDF calculated from MTD trajectory, along with the X-ray distribution of the sites, Na1–Na1 (brown), Na1–Na2 (green) and Na2–Na2 (blue). The first peak of the dynamic RDF corresponds to the Na1–Na2 distance (3.4 Å), the second peak corresponds to the Na2–Na2 distance (4.9 Å), and the third and fourth peaks respectively correspond to the first and second Na1–Na1 neighbor distances. Thus, as required by the composition, all the Na1 and Na2 sites remain occupied. The diffusion channel of Na+ revealed by the MTD trajectory also remains the same, as the one connecting Na1–Na2–Na1-sites.
Calculation of the energy profile, F, for Na4Zr2(SiO4)3 has been carried out based on the accumulated external potential in a similar fashion as in the previous case. The convergence of the profile (plotted as a function of the reaction coordinate, li) with the progress of the MTD run is demonstrated in Fig. 11. As can be seen, the profile significantly varies for run-lengths of 20 ns, 60 ns and 70 ns. For run-lengths of 80 ns and larger, the profile starts converging, measuring a barrier of about 0.34 eV. In Fig. 12, the converged free energy profile, F, from MTD simulation is compared with the average potential energy profiles of individual Na+ ions sampled from the MTD trajectory, and that from the Nudged Elastic Band (NEB) calculations. The NEB calculations are performed only between two neighboring Na1 and Na2 sites.
The free energy barriers for Na+ transport in Na4Zr2(SiO4)3 can be observed to be qualitatively diﬀerent from that of
Fig. 9 MSD of Na+ ions from MTD and MD simulations of Na4Zr2(SiO4)3 at 500 K.

Fig. 10 The Na+–Na+ RDF for Na4Zr2(SiO4)3 at 500 K, along with the distribution of Na sites (shown as bars) from the X-ray structure.
Fig. 11 Evolution of the free energy profile during the 200 ns long MTD simulation of Na4Zr2(SiO4)3 at 500 K.
NaZr2(PO4)3 in Fig. 5. Unlike in NaZr2(PO4)3, the Na2-location is now a local minimum, with the peak of the profile shifting to, roughly, mid-way along the Na1–Na2 channel. The free energy barrier of 0.34 eV obtained from MTD is in good agreement with the experimental activation barrier of 0.347 eV reported by Tran Qui et al.57
The most intriguing aspect in Fig. 12 is that the potential energy profiles of individual Na+ ions, both from MTD and NEB calculations, are in sharp contrast to the free-energy profiles. The barrier heights of the potential energy profiles are about 0.15 eV, which is much lower than the barrier obtained from the free energy profile (B0.34 eV) as well as the experimental activation energy. This behaviour is attributed to the high degree of ion–ion correlation in the system. In the NASICON solid solution Na1+xZr2SixP3ÀxO12 (0 r x r 3.0), ion–ion correlations are expected to increase with the concentration of the mobile ions x. It should be recalled that many studies in the past51,62,63 have attributed the anomalously high conductivity of

